{"stage": "definition_identify", "inputs": {"nodes": [{"position": 0, "type": "paragraph", "content": "1.3.7 Definition. Let $f$ be a function from a set $X$ into a set $Y$. If $S$ is any subset of $Y$, then the set $f^{-1}(S)$ is defined by"}, {"position": 1, "type": "math", "content": "$$f^{-1}(S) = \\{x : x \\in X \\text{ and } f(x) \\in S\\}.$$"}, {"position": 2, "type": "paragraph", "content": "The subset $f^{-1}(S)$ of $X$ is said to be the inverse image of $S$."}], "field_choices": ["algebra", "geometry", "analysis", "logic", "probability and statistics", "applied mathematics", "foundations of mathematics"]}, "outputs": {"label": "1.3.7 Definition", "number": "1.3.7", "title": "Inverse Image", "field": "foundations of mathematics"}}
